The closing date for the submission of tenders shall be 22 August.
Ombudsman: Demagogy on a compulsory model of health insurance with an additional financial burden on citizens does not pass any criticism.
Any demagogy is considered to be compulsory health insurance, which would impose a direct and increased burden of payment on citizens, without any criticism, according to the Ombudsman Juris Jansons.
Jansons met today with the Minister for Health Andes Čakš to discuss the health situation.
After the meeting, Jansons told journalists that the model of sector financing proposed by the Minister of Health is sustainable and developed health care systems, making it more accessible to patients.
He noted, however, that in this case additional funding for health care was needed, as it was not enough at the moment.
Jansons also stressed that any demagogy on compulsory health insurance, which would impose a direct and increased burden of payment on citizens, does not withstand any criticism, especially when the Dutch model is invoked.
Jansons said that the Netherlands devotes 11% of gross domestic product to health, while Latvia accounts for only 3%.
So the government and the parliament must be sufficiently responsible to realise that from this point of the freezing must rise, said the Ombudsman and added that otherwise the model proposed by the Ministry of Health (VM) will not work.
Čakša thanked the Ombudsman for his support and pointed out that the main concern was that the patient should get to the doctor, which in turn means that the healthcare system needs additional funding.
The Minister indicated that with an additional EUR 35 million planned, only the most acute cases regarding oncological patients and the remuneration of maternity specialists will be possible next year.
As a result, the VM has drawn up a plan and has submitted a request for an additional €41 million in healthcare to reduce the number of teams and investigations.
"A question about the priorities, whether it will have any resources or not," said Čakša.
This amount does not, however, include an increase in medical pay.
Commenting on the fact that medical practitioners are not excited about the fact that all three options of the Health Care Financing Model are being driven by the government for consideration of the VM, including the one that provides for additional payment to patients, Čakša said that by moving all three models, the government was given the opportunity to choose.
Jansons also added that it is possible to clearly demonstrate that Latvia is not prepared to impose additional burdens on the population by moving all three models.
It has already been reported that the VM will defend the model of health care financing, which does not involve an increase in the overall tax burden, however, requires that part of social tax be shifted to health, according to the summary of the conceptual report "On Change of the model of financing of the Latvian health care system".
At the same time, the Ministry indicated that the best option of the model of health care financing would be chosen as a result of discussions by the end of September.
