Krasnopjorov and Fadejeva: Raising a minimum wage - a miracle or a brake for the economy?
The issue of raising a minimum wage in public debate has almost the status of a saint cow: either to support promotion or to mention any non-speaking, general phrases.
In view of the considerable increase in the risk of stagnating the economy (as soon as we avoided the technical recession), it is important to stress that raising the minimum wage is not a miracle that will reduce income inequality, bring Latvia's wages closer to the Western European level and fill the state budget with one hint.
On the contrary, if the minimum wage is raised too much, it does more harm than the benefit, because it undermines the competitiveness and employment of enterprises, especially in sectors and regions with low incomes.
At the first moment it seems that despite several increases in minimum wages in the post-crisis period, the minimum wage in Latvia is not so high that raising the usual few dozens of euros per year would significantly weaken the competitiveness of companies - only 370 euros, while in some European Union (EU) countries the minimum wage is around one and a half thousand.
However, a different picture appears if we compare it with the average wage in the country (%) – the minimum wage in Latvia (44%) exceeds the EU average.
Since in Latvia the share of the minimum wage earners is significantly higher than in the neighbouring countries (in Latvia - 17%, in Lithuania - 11%, in Estonia - 6%[1]), a similar increase in the minimum wage is binding for most companies.
According to the results of the Latvijas Banka Business Survey, each fifth Latvian company replied that increasing the minimum wage in the beginning of 2014 was important or very important to increase the prices of products.
This means, firstly, that the rise in the minimum wage was partly financed by consumers (i.e. Latvian residents); secondly, the increase in prices for several companies meant a loss of competitiveness both on the domestic market and abroad (i.e. increased imports and limited exports were encouraged).
Due to lower competitiveness and smoking production volumes, it was important for almost every 15 Latvian companies to lay off their employees (which means more unemployment and emigration).
In addition, almost one in eleven companies replied that it was important for him to limit the recruitment of new employees as a result of raising the minimum wage.
It is worth remembering that in 2011 - 2013 the minimum wage in Latvia did not change.
Therefore, even if each fifth company pointed to productivity improvement as important when assessing the increase in the minimum wage for 2014, this does not mean that a similar result could be expected in 2017 (the fourth increase in the minimum wage in turn could be expected to increase productivity).
Another important result is that because of the rise in the minimum wage, it was important for several companies to increase the remuneration of employees earning more than the minimum wage.
Thus, the effect of the minimum wage was significant even for companies where none of the employees received the minimum wage.
In recent years, the rise in the minimum wage in all three Baltic States exceeded the increase in nominal labour productivity (real productivity + inflation).
A further increase in minimum wages, which is not justified by productivity gains (even though overall the rather low level in euro), will have a negative impact on companies' competitiveness and employment.
The analysis of economic averages is not enough to assess the validity of the minimum wage.
Consideration should also be given to whether raising minimum wages is "intolerant" in sectors and regions where minimum wages are most commonly used.
Results of the Bank of Latvia survey show that the largest concentration of employees with minimum wages is in small enterprises (the number of employees is between 10 and 19; 25%).
At the end of 2013, in the industrial and services sectors, the share of employees with minimum wages was higher (16% and 19% respectively) than in trade (15%), construction (11%) and financial and insurance sectors (2%).
On the other hand, for Latgale, where the minimum wage is 64% of the average wage (and more than two thirds of the average wage in the private sector), its further rise may rather harm by reducing labour demand (i.e. maintaining already high unemployment) and promoting the resilience of the shadow economy.
Some signs show that the real increases in minimum wage in 2014-2015 (by 27%) have slowed the development of Latgale.
For example, Latgale is the only region in Latvia where unemployment was higher in 2015 than in 2013.
It should be noted that there are no regions in Estonia and Lithuania that would be so far behind average wages from the rest of the country.
For example, in Estonia, the average wage in all regions is at least twice the national minimum wage.
In Lithuania, the lowest wages are in the Tauragė region, but there also the minimum wage in 2015 was 54% of the average wage (after two rapid increases in the minimum wage could reach 58 % in 2016.
The call made from time to time to raise the minimum wage to 68% of the average wage in the country (see, for example, here) lacks economic justification and is not feasible in the short and long term.
Firstly, such a high figure from the average wage, or even so close to it, is not present in any EU country.
Secondly, this would mean raising the minimum wage above the average wage in a number of economic sectors (which would mean bankruptcy and mass redundancies of companies in these sectors), such as clothing, leather products, fish processing, catering and veterinary services; moreover, it is more than the current average wage in the private sector in Latgale.
Increasing the minimum wage from January 2017 to EUR 400-410 per month, as currently proposed by the Ministry of Welfare, would make the minimum wage in Latvia (% of average salary) one of the highest in the EU.
If nominal productivity increases by 4% and minimum wages by at least twice as fast, this has clearly negative consequences for companies' competitiveness and employment.
Such negative effects will be most common in sectors and regions where the current minimum wage is often used, for example in Latgale.
The fact that we cannot afford a significant increase in the minimum wage at the moment means that other mechanisms should be put in place to support low wage earners.
An immediate effect can be achieved by travelling with personal income tax to an exempt minimum (within budget limits).
Insufficient education, inadequate education and poor quality of education acquired, as well as inadequate health status (often due to the cost of medical services and long lines) are mentioned among the real causes of income inequality.
During the survey, 521 Latvian company’s responses to the increase in the minimum wage in January 2014 were received.
The survey was carried out within the framework of the Wage Dynamics Network (WDN).
These figures represent companies with a workforce of at least 10.
This also explains the low workers’ share of minimum wages in construction.
