In the book "High Guns", in the military history of the First World War, Barbara Tačmena emphasizes how dangerous it is to give priority to the tradition of what has become known as "the tragedy of red bees."
Until the beginning of World War I, when war passed from war to war in short distances to the heavier artillery broadcast from a distance away, it became profitable to hide soldiers for as long as possible.
The British and German armies responded to these changes by replacing their bright uniforms with boring grey and brown.
However, French soldiers still wear the same red hats and pants that made them easy to use.
The proposal by Adolf Messimi, the French Minister of War, that the armies under his command could do the same, was perceived with ridicule and resistance.
