Lourda is going to take the pilgrims in the shadow of the attack
During the annual Catholic pilgrimage, people gather at Lourda Our Lady's temple.
The French security forces are in high alert state, since thousands of Catholics gather at the Lourdes temple on an annual pilgrimage in the shadow of several acts of terrorism.
Each August 15, tens of thousands of people gather at the temple at the foot of the Pyrenees Mountains for the Ascension Festival to mark the reception of Mary the virgin in heaven.
This year's pilgrimage takes place at a time when the Catholics have been shocked by the murder of an older French priest on July 26, by two Islamic extremists who invading the church in the north of France during the Mass and cut his throat.
The murder of Jacques Amel took place two weeks after a Tunisian -- the investigators claim that he was radicalized by the Jihadist on-line video materials,-- got hit by a truck at the celebration of Bastile Day in Nice, Riviera, killing 85 people.
After three large-scale attacks over 18 months, many French citizens are cautious about visiting public events.
The number of tourists fell sharply, and the authorities were concerned that this year’s number of pilgrims could fall rapidly.
However, fear of mass withdrawals did not materialize -- and some organizers say that there has even been an influx of visitors' applications at the last moment.
The arrival of some 25 000 believers is expected, including large groups from Italy and Belgium and a delegation from some 200 members of the Eastern branch of Christianity - Orthodox.
Many pilgrims have declared that they will not allow intimidation.
"We do not intend to stop living," 66-year-old visitor Christian said to AFP, describing prayer as the "one weapon" in the fight against violence.
"It is important to show that life continues," said Matier Guinean - one of the coordinators.
We will not give up our faith, our beliefs, or our way of life simply because some fanatics are trying to sow fear.
Due to concerns about security in France, a number of large-scale events have been abolished since the attack in Nice, including a huge stock market in the northern town of Lille and the European Road Cycling Championship, which was due to take place in Nice in September.
"Last week I lived in fear that my phone will call in one call to cancel applications," said Fabien Ležesne last weekend, a priest responsible for the official conduct of pilgrimage.
"On the contrary, it seems that attacks have mobilised believers," he said and announced the influx of recent applications.
Kristiāns Gels, the head of the trade association of local hotel workers, confirmed "increased interest" in pilgrimage after the attacks.
About the temple, where the virgin Mary appeared to the poor shepherd Bernadet Subir in 1858, there were extremely strict safety measures.
Approximately 250 police officers and two dozen soldiers have been assigned to protect the site, including bomb neutralisation experts and explosive detection experts in dogs.
As the temples swung through the security barriers, bags were tested at the entrance, and the number of access points was reduced from twelve to three.
Catherine Simcox, who traveled on a pilgrimage from northeast England to Lourde at the beginning of this month, described the enhanced security measures.
"By Thursday morning, armed guards were present in the temples, and then they could enter only one through the gates (with metal barriers) and the bags were searched," she said.
"This all frightened my three children, who are accustomed to Lourda, and it was hard not to scare them when they asked why it happened," she said.
It did not spoil my impressions, but it saddened me that it was necessary, and I realized that many people were calmed down by these events.
The course of the opening process on Friday has also been shortened - instead of starting up in Lourde and moving on to the temple, it will begin and end at the temple.
Other measures include the closure of the air space for flights over Lourda, the closure of streets near the traffic shrine and the replacement of waste bins to transparent plastic bags.
The French Minister for the Interior, Bernārs Kazenev, will examine security measures on Saturday.
About six million people go to Lourde every year, making it one of the world’s largest Catholic pilgrimage.
Many visitors lead relatives who are sick or disabled and who come to swim in the cave where Bernadette saw Mary, believing in the therapeutic properties of water.
In Thierry Castio, one of the organizers, described this year's gathering as "a little unusual", taking into account "the threat that roots seem to be found in France."
However, he claimed that this would not affect the quality and depth of their experience.
François, a 58-year-old volunteer who helped sick pilgrims, admitted that, in her opinion, the presence of soldiers dressed in civilian clothes was "a little depressing."
However, if it calms everyone down, it is good.
