The organizers of the Olympic Games are trying to clear the green dive pool
The Olympic divers, for which training was scheduled on Friday, came to a closed pool because the organizers needed more time to clean up the green water before the first individual competitions in Rio Olympics.
Water suddenly changed color on Tuesday, in the middle of a synchronised diving race.
The organizers claimed that even after the larger nearby pool for water polo and synchronised swimming was safe, the water race also became green.
Diving was not yet possible when athletes arrived for morning warming, although finally the pool was opened at 13.00 after local time - only 2 1/2 hours before women's 3 meter race.
The color of the water looked closer to its usual color, but still with green color.
Abby Johnson, an American dive who competes for a tramp, told her that she only came to the warmup to find out that the pool was closed without any warning.
She wrote on Twitter that "#FixTheSwamp (refine the bog) should be in fashion.
The British divers Tom Daley, who won the bronze in the synchronous diving of the platform, also commented on the status of the pool.
Hopefully, this means that in the last few days we've never gone in like a very bad thing!
Mario Andrad, the main speaker of the local committee of organisers, stressed that the pool is safe for competitions, giving the green light to the pre-selections of 3 meters.
He agreed that some athletes were disturbed by water, but he said that it was the result of the efforts to clean the pool.
"We repeat many times what we have said all the time - water does not in any way threaten the health of athletes," he said.
On the first day of such a water situation, one or two athletes complained that they had no eyes.
It was the result that the first reaction, when we saw how water becomes green, was to use one of the chemicals - chlorine - it is used very often in swimming pools.
We immediately reduced the quantity.
We checked the water once again, and that was fully in line with the parameters.
Simon Langford, the main speaker of the Marija Pole Water Sport Centre, said that the pool was closed for additional cleaning work.
He said that the decision was supported by the world's leading organisation, the FINA (International Swimming Federation).
"The reason is that the water must be calm so that the pool can return to its blue colour as soon as possible," Langford said in his statement.
Andrad said that the deterioration of the pool had surprised the organisers unprepared.
"Chemical is not an accurate science," he said.
Some things you can see last longer.
In the last few days, getting a rainwater color in the normal state made it even more difficult.
"The rains don't work," Andrad said.
He added that in the morning athletes had access to dry training, but admitted that it "was not perfect."
He explained that the change in the colour of the pool was due to an increase in alkalin levels, just as aquarium water can become green if not properly monitored.
When we started doing something about green, there were discussions about the best chemicals.
We can't use too much chemicals in water, because athletes train in it," said Andrad.
We could certainly have done better at the beginning to prevent water becoming green.
When it became green, we made a mistake again.
