Shanghai, Taipei, despite the suspension of cross-border communication, will hold a forum
However, Shanghai and Taipei will host the annual city forum from August 22 to 23 in Taipei, announced on Friday the municipality of Shanghai despite the suspension of cross-border communication mechanisms.
High-level municipal official Sha Hailin Shanghai Mayor Janga Xionga will lead a delegation on behalf of the forum by notifying the Government of Shanghai of its official microblog account with Sina Weibo.
The Forum has been organised in rotational order of both cities since 2010.
The 2016 Forum will focus on the exchange of experience in areas such as healthcare, electronic administrative services, culture and transport, with a view to "developing the exchange of experience and cooperation on various aspects" between both cities, as reported by the Shanghai Government.
The Taiwanese side has not acknowledged the agreement reached in 1992 which strengthened the principle of one China since the new leader, Tsai Ing-ven, took office in May, which has led to a suspension of communication and consultation mechanisms.
Ma Ksiaoguangs, spokesman of the State Council of the Taiwanese Affairs Bureau on land, said on Friday that peaceful cross-border relations can exist while the Taiwanese side stops at the political foundations of the 1992 agreement.
"We have an active and open attitude to the exchange of experience between cities on both sides," said MA, stressing that the essence of cross-border relations and exchange of experience between cities should be interpreted correctly.
The President of Uganda meets with the Minister of Foreign Affairs of China, hopes for closer cooperation
On Thursday, during a meeting with Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi, the President of Uganda, Jover Museveni, thanked China for its continued support for Uganda's development and expressed hope for closer cooperation.
Museveni said that China is an ancient friend of Uganda and Africa who supported the African continent's release from colonialism and later supported Africa's economic and social development.
The President mentioned the construction of the Tanzania-Zambian railway in the 1970s as proof of Chinese generous support, even when China itself was not particularly prosperous.
Museveni said that China has pursued multilateral cooperation with Uganda through both infrastructure and business investments and cultural exchanges, and added that this type of cooperation contributes to the long-term development of Uganda more than simply provided financial assistance.
He hopes that China will be able to participate in different ways in the development of Uganda's infrastructure and in the construction of an industrial park.
He also calls on Chinese to invest more in Uganda and travel it.
Wang She praised Uganda's efforts in the fields of industrialisation and modernisation of agriculture and added that China will continue to be the most reliable and ideal cooperation partner for Uganda.
Wang stated that China is ready to do its utmost to help implement Uganda's economic and social development and added that China's cooperation with Uganda is genuine and without any political considerations, as it is based on a high level of political credibility and a proven friendship over time.
He said that China could strengthen cooperation with Uganda's infrastructure and industrial park and support the development of energy and agricultural sectors in this East African people.
